ce:section.ce:para:
Selectivity of the developed approach for the estimation of ENT and CLZ was investigated, demonstrating that the developed method could accurately determine both ENT and CLZ in their tablet with excellent % recovery (98.50-101.31%) and small %RSD values (less than 1.23 %) with no interference from the excipients (

                              Table 3


                           ). Excipients such as citric acid, dextrin, mannitol, lactose, and maltose were studied in detail to eliminate the possible interference from the tablet excipients. Despite using an excess concentration of the examined excipients (1000.0 μM) which is about 100 fold of the used ENT and CLZ concentration (10 μM), no significant quenching of N,S-CDs fluorescence was induced by them, indicating the high selectivity of the proposed technique (Fig. S3a). Moreover, the method's excellent selectivity was established by the ability to determine ENT and CLZ in the presence of co-administered and other anti-Parkinson and anti-epileptic drugs, such as, levodopa, carbidopa, selegiline, pramipexol, amantadine, gabapentin, and pregabalin without any interference, since those drugs did not quench the prepared N,S-CDs' fluorescence. Furthermore, selectivity in the presence of diazepam was studied, and it was the only drug of the studied anti-epileptics that quenched the N,S-CDs' fluorescence. The tolerance limit for diazepam was measured and it was found to be 5.0 μM (Magdy et al., 2022a) (Fig. S3b). The developed method could also be applied with high % recoveries (98.70-101.30) for ENT determination in the spiked human plasma without any interference from the plasma endogenous components.
